<i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The placename is most frequent in northern England, especially Yorkshire, where there are at least 16 possible sources for the surname.","Irish: Anglicized (translated) form of Gaelic <b>Mac Sceacháin</b> ‘son of <i>Sceachán</i>’ (see   Skehan  ).","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Draighneáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Draighneán</i>’ (see   Drennan  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Thornber","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the five minor places in Yorkshire called Thornber, particularly Thornber in Halton West. The placenames derive from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn’ + <i>beorg</i> ‘hill, mound’.","Irish: adopted for various Irish names containing an element meaning ‘thorn’; compare   Thornton  ."]},{"name":"Thorton","meanings":["(1997: 465;2007: 2025; 2010: NA)","English: probably a shortened form of   Thornton  , or a habitational name from Thorton in Marnhull, Dorset, which has the same origin."]},{"name":"Skehan","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Sceacháin</b> or <b>Ó Sceacháin</b> ‘son (or descendant) of <i>Sceachán</i>’, a personal name probably based on a diminutive of <i>sceach</i> ‘briar, thorn bush’. The Gaelic name has sometimes been ‘translated’ as   Thornton  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":2,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Thorneton was born in 1380, in York, Yorkshire, England as the daughter of Robert De Thornton and E MRS ROBERT THORNTON. She married Roger of Jerdez Wayle Jodrell Esquire on 10 November 1395, in Yeardsley, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 5 sons and 3 daughters. She died in 1400, in Derby, Derbyshire, England, at the age of 20."},"et":{"1380–1400":"1380–1400","1371–1423":"1371–1423","1399–Female":"1399–Surnud","1400–1463":"1400–1463","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1404–Male":"1404–Surnud","1408–Male":"1408–Surnud","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1414–Female":"1414–Surnud","1416–Female":"1416–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","Abt 1400":"umbes 1400","1382":"1382","1371":"1371","1380":"1380","1404":"1404","1414":"1414","1423":"1423","10 Nov 1395":"10. november 1395","Abt 1399":"umbes 1399","1400":"1400","1410":"1410","1399":"1399","1463":"1463","1408":"1408","1416":"1416","Yearsley, York, Yorkshire, England":"York, Yorkshire, England","of Yeardsley,Cheshire,England":"Yeardsley, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Derby, Derbyshire, England":"Derby, Derbyshire, England","of Yeardsley, Cheshire, England":"Yeardsley, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1380–1400":"1380–1400","1371–1423":"1371–1423","1399–Female":"1399–Kuollut","1400–1463":"1400–1463","1400–Male":"1400–Kuollut","1404–Male":"1404–Kuollu